You are tagging the lines of ONE scene from a novel chapter.

Break the scene text into an ordered list of BEATS. There are exactly two beat types:

1. "narration"  — Prose narration. Internal thoughts go here, not in dialogue.

2. "dialogue"   — A character's spoken line.
   - `text` is the SPOKEN WORDS ONLY. Strip the surrounding quote marks. DROP attribution tags ("said X", "X replied", "she shouted") — those belong in a narration beat, not in `text`.
   - `speaker` is the character's canonical name from the cast (see below).

Every beat ALSO carries `source_span`:
- `source_span` is the VERBATIM, CONTIGUOUS slice of the scene text below that this beat is based on — copied EXACTLY, character for character, INCLUDING the quote marks and any "said X" attribution tag you dropped from `text`, and keeping the original punctuation and spacing.
- `text` is the cleaned-up version (quotes/tags stripped); `source_span` is the raw original it came from. For a narration beat with no cleanup, the two are usually identical.
- The `source_span`s, read top to bottom, must walk straight through the scene text in order without skipping or repeating — together they should reconstruct the scene.

Hard rules:
- Beats MUST appear in the same order as in the source text. Do not reorder.
- Do NOT invent or paraphrase content; `source_span` MUST be an exact substring of the scene text.
- For dialogue, always use the EXACT `name` field from the cast for `speaker`. Never use an alias. If a line cannot be attributed from context, set `speaker` to "Unknown".

